        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> > Vim has some detection logic for this, but it was already lost in nvim's first commit\r\n> \r\n> the logic can end up being quite a mess.\r\n\r\nTotally agreed, I don't want to blindly port a patch here 😁. The commit above was just for doing a simple comparison test against Vim. What I'm actually trying to do is gather the potentially related issues and directions first, then think about what changes make sense to scope into this PR (Anything beyond that could be handled separately in other issues), e.g.,\r\n1. I noticed you previously [mentioned](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/7846#issuecomment-357504968) that we probably shouldn't tokenize `p_sh`, and Bram also [noted](https://github.com/vim/vim/issues/459#issuecomment-361935381) that unfortunately extra flags currently have to live inside 'shell'. I assume this area could be improved in the future: A reasonable use case is users wanting to configure extra options for `:te`, such as `--login`, while `shellcmdflag` is more appropriate for non-interactive command flags.\r\n2. You also [mentioned](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/39762#issuecomment-4434111723) that we need to unify the job-control layer. Those related functions confused me before, and I assume this includes `tokenize/shellxquote/shellxescape...`, all that logic should live somewhere better. Or we could also ignore `shellquote/shellxquote/shellxescape...` logic for non-cmd shells as [mentioned here](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/28384#issuecomment-2060571893).\r\n3. There's also the [Options refactor roadmap](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/25672), which I haven't looked into deeply yet. I've also briefly thought it'd be nice if these options could support `Array` in the future, so we wouldn't need to keep reparsing things back-and-forth.\r\n\r\n> i wouldn't spend much time on this. or if we really do want it, i would move the logic to Lua, and call it via `nlua_call_excmd` or `nlua_call_vimfn`\r\n\r\nI just checked the docs — those are for implementing an Ex cmd or f_xx function. The three issues linked above are mainly about adjusting shell-related options based on 'shell', and that logic currently lives in `set_init_3`. Would this be okay to live in Lua? Or do you mean moving `ex_bang` / `vim.fn.system` to Lua?",
